
/*INTRO
All right lets start by chapters, these will be divided by the main libraries and how to use them, 
for the moments the big chapters are the following : 
1. CustomGraphics
2. CustomKeyboard
3. AwesomeUI (contains the use of 1. and 2.)

*/

/*=====================[1. CustomGraphics]=====================

Introduction : 
so lets start with a short introduction on the library, what it is and what it can do
this library is used to draw primitive shapes (such as pixels, rectangles, lines, 
triangles, and even any polygon made by a contiguous line of points using the pencil, 
you can both fill and outline for all prior primitive shapes) and text. 
It handles communication with a ILI9341 screen 
automatically which changes deppending on if you are on arduino mega or giga. In addition, 
for giga specifically there is a frame buffer (the arduino MEGA does not have enough 
memory to store a giant screen buffer, so on arduino mega we take the shortcut and directly
display on the screen, this is slower)


Before any functions lets specify a few quick things
Size struct has .w and .h  (as int16_t, because negative number shenanegans are annoying to deal with)
Point struct has .x and .y (as int16_t)
Pointd struct has .x and .y (as double)


(What it can do), functions and what they do :

the following functions are in the TFT class unless mentionned otherwise, 
to access them, refer to the "tft" object variable, and call them like this : tft.drawPixel(...);

the majority of the following functions are going to start by two things, either "draw" or "fill"
draw refers to drawing the outline, and fill refers to filling the shape, when there is no difference 
between fill or draw, draw is used by default




Size getTextBounds(const char* text, int16_t fontSize) 
description : give the text and size of font, get back its width and height
notes : this is both a global function and a function inside the TFT class (tft class's version calls the global version)

void begin()
description : begins / initializes the screen automatically (also initializes the Screen buffer on giga I believe)

void setViewport(int16_t x, int16_t y, int16_t w, int16_t h)
description : sets a specific viewport, a specific drawing zone, any pixel outside of this region will not be drawn, default is screen dimentions

void drawPixel(int16_t x, int16_t y, uint16_t color) 
description : draws a single pixel
note : you can input a Point class instead of two separate x, y numbers like so : drawPixel({1, 2}, colour);

void fillRect(int16_t x, int16_t y, int16_t w, int16_t h, uint16_t color)
description : fills a rectangle

void fillScreen(uint16_t colour)
description : fill rectangle with size of the screen

void clearScreen()
description : fill rectangle with size of the screen automatically color black

void drawRect(int16_t x, int16_t y, int16_t w, int16_t h, uint16_t colour)
description : draws the outline of a rectangle using multiple fill rect commands

void drawChar(char c, int16_t x, int16_t y, int16_t si, uint16_t colour)
description : draws a single character on the screen of desired font size "si" 
note : weird characters like \r and \b as well as any terminal specific characters 
       are not supported, backtracking text is not supported

void setCursor(int16_t cursor_x, int16_t cursor_y, int8_t fontSize, uint16_t fontColor, int16_t cursor_x_start)
description : used with tft "print" and "println" functions, this is used to set the position the text is going to be written
note : this function can be called to set only the x and y, or to set x, y, fontsize and color

void s_print(const char* s)
description : singular print statements that are used to convert the input (multiple input types possible) and print it using drawChar
note : supported types are the following : String, const char*, long long, unsigned long long, long, unsigned long, int, unsigned int, unsigned char, double
       note that some number number s_print are broken

void print(...)
description : any number of input print function, that prints one by one the inputs with nothing in between (this behaves like a util function nammed print and println), 
              to print, just imagine all spaces and commas between arguments dissapeared, and thats what it'll print
examples : printing with this function looks like this : println("hello world, I eat ",5," appeles every day but sometimes ",10,",however they are red");
// note : annoying quirk of print, don't use global print without "::" in front because you'll call this function instead of the global one, you don't know how many times that happent

void println()
description : same concept as print(...) but it adds a new line at the end

void drawText(const char* s, int16_t x, int16_t y, int16_t si, uint16_t colour, bool wrapText)
description : draws text at desired position, desired font size and colour, you have the option to wrap text 
note : wrapText wraps characters only, so a bit jarring to read, I do not recommend
    
void drawLine(double x1, double y1, double x2, double y2, uint16_t colour)
description : draws a line
note : x1, y1 and x2, y2 can be replaced by Point structs like so : drawLine({x1, y1}, pointVariable, colour) or variable version

void drawTriangle(int16_t x1, int16_t y1, int16_t x2, int16_t y2, int16_t x3, int16_t y3, uint16_t colour)
description : draws the outline of a triangle
note : the coordinates can be replaced by Point structs

void fillTriangle(int16_t x1, int16_t y1, int16_t x2, int16_t y2, int16_t x3, int16_t y3, uint16_t colour)
description : fills a triangle
note : the coordinates can be replaced by Point structs

void setPencil(int16_t x, int16_t y)
description : set down the pencil used to START drawing lines connecting dots (resets any previous drawing progress)

void resetPencil()
description : this function makes the next dashPencil call act the same as a setPencil call, which essentially resets the pencil but not the same as setPencil

void dashPencil(int16_t x, int16_t y)
description : create a line from the previous point to the point defined in the function (dash pencil to the next point)

void drawPencil(uint16_t color)
description : this finalizes the pencil path and draws it (draws outline) (this does not reset drawing progress)

void fillPencil(uint16_t color)
description : this finalizes the pencil path and fills it (draws outline + inside outline) (this does not reset drawing progress you can theoretically call drawPencil() to draw outline on top of that)

void drawPencilPoints(uint16_t color)
description : this draws all points you dashed your pencil through


=============================================================*/

/*=====================[1. CustomKeyboard]=====================

Introduction : 
this library can either simulate a keyboard or handle real keyboard input
(real keyboard input is only available on giga since its the only one that supports usb devices)
this library either uses a mediocre emulation of the keyboard or a half working library called
USBHostGiga and makes it usable in our context
this library is sorta badly made and diservse a revamp soon that I am yet to do because of lazyness
this text will specify how to use it within the context of AwesomeUI library, there are other functions
but the main ones you're probably maybe going to use are here, the rest AwesomeUI will probably handle

(What it can do), functions and what they do:

the following functions are from the "Keyboard" class and require the use of the "kbd" object variable to use like so : "kbd.checkForKey(KEY_ESCAPE)"

void begin()
description : initializes the keyboard

bool checkForKey(uint8_t key)
description : simple function that checks if you are currently holding the specific key

bool keysClear()
description : this function is used to check if there are no keys being pressed at the moment (this does not include modifier keys like ctrl, shift or alt)


=============================================================*/

/*=====================[1. AwesomeUI]=====================

Introduction:
in this library, there is so many things to digest, but I'll try to cut it short and briefly go over everything
to the best of my abilities


GLOBAL FUNCTIONS:

bool touched()
description : function automatically used by the library to get if the screen is being touched
note : the giga doesn't have touch anymore, so touch relies on keyboard input with arrows and a cursor,
       but other wise it works the same as the mega

Point getPoint()
description : used in tandem with touched, gets the location of the point touched, AwesomeUI already handles this tho

bool collide(int x1, int y1, int w1, int h1, int x2, int y2, int w2, int h2)
description : input two rectangles and get if they touch or not



UI CLASS FUNCTIONS ("ui" object) : 

the input variables of the following functions containing "add" (to add a ui element) contain the same variable names as the input paramatters and can be changed at runtime


Text& addText(const char* id, String text, int fontsize, uint16_t colour, T1 x, T2 y);
description : adds a text to the screen
note : automatically returns the reference of the Text& element that you just created

Text& getText(const char* id)
description : gets a Text reference by inputing id of the desired element


for briefty, we'll just say that all "add...(...)" functions have their "get...(const char* id)" counterpart
and all "add...(...)" return the element they just created


Button& addButton(const char* id_input, String text, int fontsize, uint16_t colour, T3 textOffsetX, T4 textOffsetY, bool background, uint16_t backgroundcolor, T1 posX, T2 posY, uint16_t width, uint16_t height, Function<void, Button*, bool> function, bool toggle)
@brief adds a button
@param id the id of the ui element (can be changed once set)
@param text the text that the button is displaying
@param fontsize the size of the text
@param colour the colour of the text (use "color()" function to input color with rgb (0 to 255 for each color))
@param tx the position in x axis of the text, can be inputed as number (Ex:1, 2, 10, 20, etc...) or as string (Ex:"middle", "left", "right", etc...)
@param ty the position in y axis of the text, can be inputed as number (Ex:1, 2, 10, 10, etc...) or as string (Ex:"middle", "top", "down", etc...)
@param background is there a background? (in the case that there is no backgorund, the position of the text will take over and won't simply be the offset position based on the background position)
@param backgroundColor the color of the background (if there is no background, the color you input doesn't matter)
@param x the position in the x axis of the background
@param y the position in the y axis of the background
@param w the width of the background
@param h the height of the background
@param onClick a function that plays whenever the button changes states
@param toggle the state of the button. Is it a toggle or a simple, push down to activate, stop pushing to deactivate
@retval returns a button reference, (you can globaly initialize a button and set its variable to the button)

Menu& addMenu(const char* id, T1 x, T2 y, int16_t w, int16_t h, uint8_t background, uint16_t colour)
@brief adds a button
@param id the id of the ui element (can be changed once set)
@param x the position in the x axis of the background
@param y the position in the y axis of the background
@param w the width of the background
@param h the height of the background
@param background is there a background?
@param colour the color of the background (if there is no background, the color you input doesn't matter)
@retval returns a Menu reference, (you can globaly initialize a Menu and set its variable to the Menu)

Window& addWindow(const char* id, uint16_t colour, T1 x, T2 y, uint16_t w, uint16_t h)
description : adds a window, windows can contain other UIelements, 
              and to create them within a window, you just call the same "add...(...)" 
              functions as before, but on the Window object, not the UI object ("ui")
              "get...(...)" also require you to call them on the object you desire 
              search for an element with specific id

Terminal& addTerminal(const char* id_input, T1 window_x, T2 window_y, int16_t window_w, int16_t window_h, uint16_t backgroundColor, uint16_t textColor)
description : adds a terminal, its a lazy class that spawns in a window with a text inside of it and handles inputs to that text box, don't use it please, its bad

void remove(const char* id)
description : tanos snap an element out of existence, if there are two elements with the same id, it will take the first one in the list (first one or last one created, who knows)

void remove(UIelement* ptr)
description : more precision tanos snap, if you know the pointer to the element instead. All element classes like "Text" or "Window" are descendents from UIelement class

void begin()
description : this function initializes all other libraries that AwesomeUI relies on, this incluedes Customkeyboard, CustomGraphics, Utility (didn't talk about that one much but meh whatever)

void update()
description : it updates / draws all elements to the screen (displays them too), it also handles inputs and keyboard inputs


=============================================================*/

/*TO ADD LATER MISSING INFO: 

oh right,
great questions,
I'll add them

so yes, on arduino GIGA since there is a frame buffer you need to "empty" that frame buffer to see the result on the screen
this is done automatically by AwesomeUI after all ui.update calls
damn I didn't talk about that too, god damn it
I didn't talk about ui.begin either.. damn it
anyways, to do so (empty the frame buffer onto the screen) call : "displayFrameBuffer()" function is global

OH RIGTH COLORS TOO
thats a great thing you ask
my function inputs have as inputs uint16_t for colors, this is because each pixel of the ILI9341 screen has 16 bit colors, wait is that really how you say it, anwyays, yeah, so its not like the usuall thing where you have 0-255 0-255 0-255, its something fucked like 0-32 0-64 0-32, anyways, who cares bcs I made a conversion function that takes in 0-255 and automatically gives back the correct (but lower quality version) uint16_t version
refer to the rgb(0-255, 0-255, 0-255) function to do that
also there is a function that does the same thing with the name of "color" so don't use a global variable named "color"
thats why we use colour for the class variables, but now that I realise it its stupid, whatever

yes we do have contants colors, pre made basically here they are : 
TFT_BLACK
TFT_NAVY
TFT_DARKGREEN
TFT_DARKCYAN
TFT_MAROON
TFT_PURPLE
TFT_OLIVE
TFT_LIGHTGREY
TFT_DARKGREY
TFT_BLUE
TFT_GREEN
TFT_CYAN
TFT_RED
TFT_MAGENTA
TFT_YELLOW
TFT_WHITE
TFT_ORANGE
TFT_GREENYELLOW
TFT_PINK
TFT_BROWN
TFT_GOLD
TFT_SILVER
TFT_SKYBLUE
TFT_VIOLET
they were... sorta stolen from TFT_eSPI lib but meh who cares

also, something that I did not mention, for function inputs like 
onClick
just set lambdas to them
I sorta am feeling lazy rn and I don't want to explain all of the specific inputs for if you want to set a Function variable, so just let me know what function variable you want to set and I'll tell you what the inputs of your lambda are
and yes, I made a custom std::function equivalent class (named "Function")

lets answer to those questions one by one
1. yes, position is relative to an element, if your button inside of a window has position 0, 0 it will be at the top left corner of the window, not at the top left corner of the screen (unless the top left corner of the window happens to also be the top left corner of the screen)
2. lambda inputs, yes the correct input for onClick is "Button* b, bool state" and yes my Function should support capturing variables

3. yes z_indexing is a thing.. I didn't mention it tho.. So by default my program draws from first created to last created (or maybe its inverted, who knows) but if you want to be sure, you can set the "z_index" (a variable that all elements have, bcs they inherit from UIelement calss which has that), from memory a higher z_index means its more in front, and lower means its more at teh back (doesn't change apparent size on the screen, just who gets drawn first) also z_index is a int8_t, so don't put a extremly large z_index

4. yes image support... is a critical.. missing feature sadly, I should definitively add that next
*/

